<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-09-03T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-09-03T03:00:00-05:00" n="313" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d313">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/5489: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Cunningham</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-09-03T16:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">September 3,
                                        1924—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received September 3—6:21
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Reliably informed that hostilities broke out at 10 o’clock this morning
                            at Hwangtu 15 miles west of Shanghai between forces of Military Governor
                            Chi and Commissioner of Defense Ho. British, American, Japanese, French,
                            Italian naval contingent in the harbor prepared to land forces to
                            protect foreign settlement if necessary. French consul general has just
                            advised that French naval forces will land at 5 p.m. today in the French
                            concession.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Cunningham</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
